&lt;p&gt;Make your sleeping environment as boring as possible. You donâ€™t want to have any excitement before you sleep or after you wake up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The most common culprit of entertainment in bed is the phone. If you have something else that you love you use in bed like a tablet, I suggest you move that away too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are two goals this achieves:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Improves sleep&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Helps with getting out of bed&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;no-way-around-it&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;markdownIt-Anchor&#34; href=&#34;#no-way-around-it&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; No way around it&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Before I put my phone in another room, I constantly checked it in bed. I would message my friends. I would check every social media app I had. I would watch YouTube to sleep. I thought it was good because I kept doing it and I was so used to falling asleep with entertainment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As long as your phone is within reach when you wake up, thereâ€™s an incredible temptation to use it in bed. I donâ€™t know about you but Iâ€™ve stayed in bed for hours mucking around on my phone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have no self-control at all, so I control my environment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;put-your-phone-in-another-room&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;markdownIt-Anchor&#34; href=&#34;#put-your-phone-in-another-room&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Put your phone in another room&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Itâ€™s a simple idea, but not easy. It feels like youâ€™re giving away your baby. But the resistance is good. It means youâ€™re killing an addiction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Choose a room with a place to charge your phone. This could be the living room, kitchen, or in my case, a study room. Leave your phone there and in the morning, check it after youâ€™ve left your bed, not before.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;use-melatonin-as-insurance&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;markdownIt-Anchor&#34; href=&#34;#use-melatonin-as-insurance&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; ğŸ’Š Use Melatonin as Insurance&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Iâ€™ve left the most controversial for last. If you donâ€™t want to take any substances, you can skip this section.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Melatonin is a natural hormone that regulates the sleep-wake cycle. Your body produces it at night to help you sleep. But you can also take it as a pill.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can get it in the United States without a prescription. Since melatonin is found in some foods, the U.S. Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act of 1994 allows it to be sold as a dietary supplement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;dosage&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;markdownIt-Anchor&#34; href=&#34;#dosage&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Dosage&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;span class=&#34;exturl&#34; data-url=&#34;aHR0cDovL25ld3MubWl0LmVkdS8yMDAxL21lbGF0b25pbi0xMDE3&#34;&gt;2001 study&lt;/span&gt; found that the ideal dosage is 0.3 mg. The lowest amount of a melatonin dose Iâ€™ve found is 1mg. If you can find 0.3 mg, then good for you. I use 1mg and cut it into half (0.5 mg). Itâ€™s not exactly 0.3 mg, but it works for me. Iâ€™ve tried different dosages, including up to 10 mg, and none of them worked as well as taking less.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;regulate-your-sleep-schedule&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;markdownIt-Anchor&#34; href=&#34;#regulate-your-sleep-schedule&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt; Regulate your sleep schedule&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you donâ€™t get to sleep on time consistently, melatonin isnâ€™t going to save you. I tried to cheat the system. It didnâ€™t work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nevertheless, youâ€™re sometimes going to fail. You might sleep too late. You might have a coffee too late in the day. You might wake up in the afternoon and have trouble sleeping early.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I fail. Iâ€™m not a perfectly disciplined monk. When it happens, I take melatonin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even though melatonin isnâ€™t considered an addictive substance, be cautious. Thereâ€™s no evidence melatonin has dangerous effects, but you can build up a tolerance for it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My recommendation is to use melatonin when you mess up your sleep schedule and canâ€™t get to sleep at your bedtime because youâ€™re too awake â€” but donâ€™t allow that to happen too often.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I said a lot about sleep. Thatâ€™s because most of waking up early is sleeping early, and it isnâ€™t easy to sleep early. There are sacrifices to be made. If youâ€™re willing to make them, you can become an early bird.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are glamorous parts to waking up early. You get to be productive. You get the feeling of accomplishing something before anybody else does. You get hours of solitude in a solitude-deprived, technology-focused world. I love it.&lt;/p&gt;
